columns.text:
The **spot rate** is the *exchange rate in a spot trade*. The **spot trade** is an agreement to exchange currencies based on the exchange rate on that date and must be settled within two business days.
&nbsp;

A **forward trade** is an agreement to *exchange currency in the future*. The *exchange rate in the agreement* of a forward trade is called a **forward exchange rate.**

First, we will determine the cost of the expansion in dollars.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Cost of Expansion in \$} &= \dfrac{\text{Cost of Expansion in SF }}{\text{Spot Rate}}\\[15pt]
&= \dfrac{\text{SF 13,800,000}}{\text{SF 1.09}}\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\text{\$ 12,660,550}}
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;

The investment is worth **$ 12,660,550**.

Next, we will determine the expected cash flow in dollar in year 1.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Cash Flow in \$} &= \dfrac{\text{Cash Flow in SF }}{\text{Exchange Rate}}\\[15pt]
&= \dfrac{\text{SF 3,900,000}}{\text{SF 1.0791}}\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\text{\$ 3,614,123}}
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;

The cash flow in Year 1 when converted into dollars is **$ 3,614,123**.

Next, we will determine the expected cash flow in dollar in year 2.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Cash Flow in \$} &= \dfrac{\text{Cash Flow in SF }}{\text{Exchange Rate}}\\[15pt]
&= \dfrac{\text{SF 3,900,000}}{\text{ SF 1.0683}}\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\text{\$ 3,650,660}}
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;

The cash flow in Year 2 when converted into dollars is **$ 3,650,660**.

